olidate on our infrastructural equipment and other logistical holdings to address critical welfare and operational requirements needed to boost the capacity to meet our maritime security obligations.” He spoke thus:”The Nigerian Navy has over the years continued to make useful contributions to our national economy despite tight fiscal conditions. These have been achieved through hard work, strict adherence to an established transformation plans and diligent fiscal discipline. “Accordingly,the Nigerian Navy remains ready and capable to do much more if availed the necessary platforms and materials. “The service therefore continues to count on the tireless support of this distinguished Senate as partners in progress towards emplacing the Nigerian Navy that will optimally makes the aspirations of this great nation for the benefit of future generations. “I am particularly appreciative of the enviable support of the committee on its role during the 2020 budget defence which has since been graciously assented to by President Muhammad Buhari. “This is highly commendable and a testimony of harmonious relationship between both the executive and legislative arms of government. “Going forward, the Nigerian Navy intends to build on the ongoing fleet recapitalization programme by working towards urgent acquisition of more operational platforms. “The service will be expecting a total of 56 assorted platforms including ships and aircraft within the year 2020. “The Nigerian Navy also intends to consolidate on our infrastructural equipment and other logistical holdings to address critical welfare and operational requirements needed to boost the capacity to meet our maritime security obligations.”   The Chief of Naval Staff (CNS), Vice Adm. Ibok-Ette Ibas, on Wednesday said the Nigerian Navy was being repositioned for enhanced operational efficiency in light of the emerging security threats in the nation’s maritime space. May 31, 2017 In "News" In its renewed effort to equip its workforce and develop requisite capacities to drive indigenous technology, the Nigerian Navy, commissioned a standard jetty and other projects in Lagos, as part of activities to mark its 63rd anniversary. June 1, 2019 In "News" By Joseph Erunke The Nigerian Navy has advocated the establishment of a special court to try maritime offences, saying it was necessary to expeditiously dispense maritime cases. The position of the service came as it said lack of enough ships to cover Nigeria's waters was in no small measures, affecting… October 10, 2019 In "News"